Let me start out by saying that Gary Danko is the best restaurant I have ever been to. The food, the service, and the ambiance combine to make a spectacular night. The only down side of this restaurant is the difficulty of getting a reservation, but once you are in everything is amazing. A cherry on top is that Gary Danko is also reasonably priced compared to other restaurants of the same class. I highly recommend Gary Danko to anyone looking for excellent food and impeccable service.

ONE WORD = INCREDIBLE! I recently was surprised by my date as they took me to Gary Danko for my birthday. I had a hint that we might be going to Gary Danko but was not really sure till we stumbled upon the dark street and darkened windows. But what's inside will surely leave you breathless. We had reservations for the last time slot of the night, 10pm a few days ago and we were seated once a table was available. From there on, the experience to the food was impressive. The staff had chosen a big table for us near the flowers and the big corner window with a good view of the entire restaurant. The staff had plated the silverware and plates next to each other so that my date and I would be sitting next to each other, rather than across. Great decision on their part! But what one staff member did for us, had set the tone for the rest of the night. Instead of us struggling to squeeze onto the table's booth seats by means of a tiny space, the staff member moved the entire table for us to sit down and moved it back comfortably for us to sit down. Absolutely flawless. Even though the restaurant closes at 10pm and our reservation was at 10pm, we did not feel rushed whatsoever as we sat and ate for almost 2 hours. My date and I decided upon the 4 course pre-fix which is $85 a person. However, that 4-course meal turned out to be 6 courses as we were treated to some complimentary items. These were my courses: Course 1: Lemongrass curry soup. Amazing curry with exotic flavors. It was simple, elegant and not heavy either. Course 2: A fried bread starter with shaved salmon, caviar and creme fraiche on top. This was amazing and I still don't know the name of it. Can anyone help? Course 3: Lobster salad with Asian pear, mangoes with lime-cilantro remoulade and it was just to die for. I could eat this salad all day. Course 4: My 1st main entree, Maine Lobster with a potato puree. This was so good that I scarfed it down so fast that I didn't even see my date blink. Course 5: The pork belly and pork medallions with parsnip puree. This was good but the pork medallions were a bit raw. Raw meats kind of scare me but not bad. I would have loved more pork belly instead. Course 6: Orange sherbet with a sweet orange biscuit. This rocked my world and the presentation was just over the top. To end my dinner with this and some mini desserts on the side was the perfect icing on my birthday cake. And not to forget, looking into my date's eyes! Haha lol... But one last comment, my date's 3rd course was the lobster risotto and that dish just keeps coming back to haunt me. That was probably my favorite dish of the whole night and I wish I can order that togo because it was THAT AMAZING! Overall, a perfect night with flawless service. I still remember our server's name, Suzanne. She was so friendly and always gave us a smile. She thought we were cute when we searched around the restaurant at the end of our dinner to give her a THANKS for the great evening. I cannot wait to come back to Gary Danko and it has definitely raised the bar on other restaurants. I hope to see the more casual version open up soon down the street as well as come back to Gary Danko and receive the same treatment or even better! Even though my date and I were only wearing sweaters (while the rest of the patrons had suits, ties, dresses on), we were treated as if we were royalty. This place is one of my top 3 meals ever in the Bay Area and you won't be disappointed. Why else would I write such a long review right? Check out my photos too! =) Thank you Gary Danko, Suzanne and the staff at one of my new favorite places to splurge!

food and service was absolutely wonderful. the portions were bigger than normal Michelin Star restaurants and the waiters/waitresses are very nice. Food was so good and i savored every bite!

Amazing service, delicious food! From the minute we walked in, we felt welcomed. The hostess took my coat immediately and although our table was not yet ready, the hostess routinely came to us at the bar to let us know the status of our table. Stellar in every respect. Come every year with my wife. Perfect every time. The service is on point without being over bearing. Food is excellent without being too pretentious. Perfect all around.

Took my wife here for a gourmet night out while on vacation in NYC. I'm teetering between 4 and 5 stars for the review. First off-The service is timely, warm and friendly, and as spectacular as you would hope for at a restaurant like this. The presentation of the table settings was unique and beautiful. 5 stars for ambiance and service. They also send you with a nice little breakfast cake on your way out. The food was closer to a four star experience just based on the price. I ordered the risotto for my appetizer-it was quite good, but nothing spectacular. My wife ordered some type of corn soup-wasn't my cup of tea, but she enjoyed it. Appetizers just hit the mark. Entrees we ordered were the Bronzino (one of the recommendations) and the Filet. The Bronzino fell a little flat to me; as the skin was nice and crispy, but the fish lacked any salt and I didn't quite dig the citrus sauce and mandarin oranges around it. My wife's filet was cooked perfectly, but flavor was slightly lacking. Dessert was the highlight of the food-my wife's trio of creme brulee and my chocolate souffle were delicious. For 2 appetizers, 2 drinks, 2 entrees, and 2 desserts, the bill came out to be about $300. We each ordered the minimum 3 course meal; it was plenty of food, but for the quality I felt it was closer to a $150 above average dinner vs. a $300 once in a lifetime dinner for the quality of the food. However, the service and ambiance was at a $300 meal level. I'm willing to give it 5 stars because I do believe there are probably some other entrees that maybe I would have enjoyed more based on some of the other food that we had ate or saw at other tables.

Every course with the wine pairings were absolutely amazing. We will definitely be going back here. It's an upscale place with very nice ambiance. Not stuffy, just wonderful. I had the farm egg, foie gras, filet of beef, and lemon souffle with wine pairings. We were so stuffed when we left. I might consider the four-course next time as their portions are actually quite large. The Sommelier was very kind to remove California wines from the pairings, as I prefer the dryer European vints. If you are into culinary perfection, this is your place in SF.

Many on chowhound, here on Yelp, and others think this place is the be all and end all, but honestly, meh. It's certainly not bad, maybe even good in some aspects, but it's not somewhere I'd go for a special occasion (though that's what we went for) because it's actually a pretty informal feeling place, even though most people dress up. Service is friendly, but beyond trying to deliver plates at the same time, service is as informal as any random decent restaurant, to the extent that service people come up and say "are you done with that?" even when it's pretty apparent that you're not. I'm sure some of that has to do with turning the table, but why come here, spend what it costs, and feel rushed? Can't fault the food too much, except to say that it's a bit old-fashioned, kind of stuck in the 90s cuisine feeling. I'm sure it's all well and good for the main clientele, so more power to them, but for me, not particularly interesting. The standout course for my palate was the risotto, nicely flavored and textured. Post meal update: staph enteritis (aka food poisoning). Most likely culprit, the scallop dish. Result: day off from work feeling terrible, and a dr visit. Post post-meal update: emailed the restaurant just so they knew, for the benefit of future diners. They called back and offered an apology and talked about their procedure for responding to this while at the same time sounding disbelieving and repeating "you're the only one who has been affected". Like it has to affect all their customers before anyone is believed? We didn't tell them about our illness looking for anything, nor would we take it up if it were offered in this case, but feel that the restaurant should offer compensation, and they did not. I will relate another incident from the meal -- they delivered an incorrect dish. Whoops, they'll bring the correct one out right away. Fine, short delay but never mind. But then, on the bill, we were charged for the extra item, which we pointed out, and they corrected it, and, simply, sorry. Two service mistakes in one meal, at this supposed standard of restaurant? And sorry is all we get? I guess it's just a reflection of the philosophy of this place. Tightwads. Post post post-meal update: As an preface to the next paragraph, I'll add another service faux-pas. we ordered the dessert that they make tableside. At some point, we do see a cart roll up, but the guy making the stuff is talking and laughing with an adjoining table, so we think, oh, he's making it for them and we'll get the show again when he makes ours. But no, it *was* ours, done with no introduction and we get a plate slapped down in front of us after he left. Huh? This is service? Honestly, I have no idea where the vaunted service that others write about was. Someone else we know went here a week or so later, with a chef buddy who the restaurant knows. When he described his meal and service, it was like "we went to the same restaurant?". I can understand that things can be done for VIPs, but in contrast, we, during our meal, felt like 2nd class citizens, perhaps even 3rd. A good restaurant might give extra special service to VIPs, but they will not give inferior service to ordinary customers. Danko did to us.

    ONE WORD = INCREDIBLE!

    I recently was surprised by my date as they took me to Gary Danko for my birthday. I had a hint that we might be going to Gary Danko but was not really sure till we stumbled upon the dark street and darkened windows. But what's inside will surely leave you breathless. We had reservations for the last time slot of the night, 10pm a few days ago and we were seated once a table was available. From there on, the experience to the food was impressive.

    The staff had chosen a big table for us near the flowers and the big corner window with a good view of the entire restaurant. The staff had plated the silverware and plates next to each other so that my date and I would be sitting next to each other, rather than across. Great decision on their part! But what one staff member did for us, had set the tone for the rest of the night. Instead of us struggling to squeeze onto the table's booth seats by means of a tiny space, the staff member moved the entire table for us to sit down and moved it back comfortably for us to sit down. Absolutely flawless.

    Even though the restaurant closes at 10pm and our reservation was at 10pm, we did not feel rushed whatsoever as we sat and ate for almost 2 hours. My date and I decided upon the 4 course pre-fix which is $85 a person. However, that 4-course meal turned out to be 6 courses as we were treated to some complimentary items.

    These were my courses:
    Course 1: Lemongrass curry soup. Amazing curry with exotic flavors. It was simple, elegant and not heavy either.
    Course 2: A fried bread starter with shaved salmon, caviar and creme fraiche on top. This was amazing and I still don't know the name of it. Can anyone help?
    Course 3: Lobster salad with Asian pear, mangoes with lime-cilantro remoulade and it was just to die for. I could eat this salad all day.
    Course 4: My 1st main entree, Maine Lobster with a potato puree. This was so good that I scarfed it down so fast that I didn't even see my date blink.
    Course 5: The pork belly and pork medallions with parsnip puree. This was good but the pork medallions were a bit raw. Raw meats kind of scare me but not bad. I would have loved more pork belly instead.
    Course 6: Orange sherbet with a sweet orange biscuit. This rocked my world and the presentation was just over the top. To end my dinner with this and some mini desserts on the side was the perfect icing on my birthday cake. And not to forget, looking into my date's eyes! Haha lol...

    But one last comment, my date's 3rd course was the lobster risotto and that dish just keeps coming back to haunt me. That was probably my favorite dish of the whole night and I wish I can order that togo because it was THAT AMAZING! Overall, a perfect night with flawless service. I still remember our server's name, Suzanne. She was so friendly and always gave us a smile. She thought we were cute when we searched around the restaurant at the end of our dinner to give her a THANKS for the great evening.

    I cannot wait to come back to Gary Danko and it has definitely raised the bar on other restaurants. I hope to see the more casual version open up soon down the street as well as come back to Gary Danko and receive the same treatment or even better! Even though my date and I were only wearing sweaters (while the rest of the patrons had suits, ties, dresses on), we were treated as if we were royalty. This place is one of my top 3 meals ever in the Bay Area and you won't be disappointed. Why else would I write such a long review right? Check out my photos too! =) Thank you Gary Danko, Suzanne and the staff at one of my new favorite places to splurge!

    Many on chowhound, here on Yelp, and others think this place is the be all and end all, but honestly, meh. It's certainly not bad, maybe even good in some aspects, but it's not somewhere I'd go for a special occasion (though that's what we went for) because it's actually a pretty informal feeling place, even though most people dress up. Service is friendly, but beyond trying to deliver plates at the same time, service is as informal as any random decent restaurant, to the extent that service people come up and say "are you done with that?" even when it's pretty apparent that you're not. I'm sure some of that has to do with turning the table, but why come here, spend what it costs, and feel rushed? Can't fault the food too much, except to say that it's a bit old-fashioned, kind of stuck in the 90s cuisine feeling. I'm sure it's all well and good for the main clientele, so more power to them, but for me, not particularly interesting. The standout course for my palate was the risotto, nicely flavored and textured.

    Post meal update: staph enteritis (aka food poisoning). Most likely culprit, the scallop dish. Result: day off from work feeling terrible, and a dr visit.

    Post post-meal update: emailed the restaurant just so they knew, for the benefit of future diners. They called back and offered an apology and talked about their procedure for responding to this while at the same time sounding disbelieving and repeating "you're the only one who has been affected". Like it has to affect all their customers before anyone is believed? We didn't tell them about our illness looking for anything, nor would we take it up if it were offered in this case, but feel that the restaurant should offer compensation, and they did not. I will relate another incident from the meal -- they delivered an incorrect dish. Whoops, they'll bring the correct one out right away. Fine, short delay but never mind. But then, on the bill, we were charged for the extra item, which we pointed out, and they corrected it, and, simply, sorry. Two service mistakes in one meal, at this supposed standard of restaurant? And sorry is all we get? I guess it's just a reflection of the philosophy of this place. Tightwads.

    Post post post-meal update:
    As an preface to the next paragraph, Â I'll add another service faux-pas. we ordered the dessert that they make tableside. At some point, we do see a cart roll up, but the guy making the stuff is talking and laughing with an adjoining table, so we think, oh, he's making it for them and we'll get the show again when he makes ours. But no, it *was* ours, done with no introduction and we get a plate slapped down in front of us after he left. Huh? This is service? Honestly, I have no idea where the vaunted service that others write about was.

    Someone else we know went here a week or so later, with a chef buddy who the restaurant knows. When he described his meal and service, it was like "we went to the same restaurant?". I can understand that things can be done for VIPs, but in contrast, we, during our meal, felt like 2nd class citizens, perhaps even 3rd. Â A good restaurant might give extra special service to VIPs, but they will not give inferior service to ordinary customers. Danko did to us.
